reviewText: The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice This is a well done movie made for TV that is good for the whole family. It has drama, comedy, horror, and a mix of just good old sentimentality.

The Librarian series is MUST SEE TV at its best.  When the video wasteland is filled with reality shows I look forward each year when Flynn goes off on another adventure.  And there so many entertaining and informative possibilities with this series they MUST go on and on and on.  I'd like to see more books if the movies are going to stop.  And I'd like to see more of the Library maybe even with compulation books about the Library and Flynn written by readers.  To the powers that be...Don't Drop the ball on this.  Give the PEOPLE what they want....for once.
I love The Librarian! All of them! Hope they can come up with more ideas for more movies!

I stumbled on the second Librarian movie by accident one night and after watching it was very impressed. When I heard the 3rd movie being advertised on tv I couldn't wait to see it. Afterward I ordered 1 & 2 so I could watch them over and over. To me, they're a wonderful mix of Indiana Jones & Davinci Code. Noah Wyle is a superb actor (I'm an ER fan) and he brings much charisma to his role. I've always loved Jane Curtin and Bob Newhart and these 3 together are a magical team. I'm pre-ordering Curse of the Judas Chalice so I can have the set at my disposal for frequent viewing. All 3 are entertainment at its best!

Third time around the Librarian decides to take a vacation to New Orleans where he meets a vampire who gives him an amulet to protect, while ex KGB agents try to steal it, so they can raise Count Dracula from the dead to help "restore mother Russia back to her glory"

This one didn't seem to have the spirit of the first 2 movies, however it was a refreshing change to get out of the jungles and such and into the swamps filled with pirate ships, vampires, tombs, amulets and the full intention of making 100 more sequels.

This is the third of the "Librarian" TV movies with Noah Wyle and I think they keep improving each time out.  With all the vampire movies and books out there right now, it must have seemed only natural to pit Flynn against the undead and it did not disappoint! Action, humor and mystery in good combination. Bob Newhart and Jane Curtain were excellent as always and Excaliber had a very nice scene. That sword has definitely become a character in itself! The only downer is that I kept hearing that this was the final one and I'm really hoping that either I heard wrong or they change their mind! Great production values and good FX but these movies are definitely story and character-driven.  Make more please!!

- An outraged Flynn Carsen (on having his tuxedo shirt ripped during a sword duel): "This is rented!" - His evil (yet urbane) opponent: "Of course it is." It's always a guilty pleasure catching up with the Librarian, whose job is to guard history's secret relics and treasures, some of these magical in nature and all stowed away in the hidden chambers of the Metropolitan Library of New York. Flynn Carsen is sort of like a modern-day Indiana Jones, except that he's awkward and plenty nerdy. But Flynn does keep his wits about him, and, after years of holding down the Librarian gig, he now boasts experience and smidgens of confidence. This current Librarian may fumble about some, but it's always fun seeing how he'll get out of whatever scrape. The more things change... The movie opens with Flynn at a posh event applying the finishing touches to his tuxedo. He then navigates down a stairway, sips champagne, and then does a spit take with the champagne. Which goes to show that, even after all this time, Flynn Carsen is still refreshingly hapless. But, after this latest escapade, which climaxes in a sword fight, Flynn Carsen is officially burnt out (his girlfriend dumping him has something to do with it). Back at the library, by virtue of sheer grousing, he gets himself some time off and ends up flying to New Orleans, all gigged out in bow tie and panama hat. So, as they say in the Big Easy, laissez les bon temps roullez. Or not. The holiday rapidly turns into a desperate relic hunt, with Flynn taking on ex-KGB agents, voodoo magic, and the undead. Along the way, he partners up with a mysterious chanteuse to rescue a kidnapped scientist. The relic in question is the rumored Judas Chalice, of which origin dates back to Judas Iscariot and his 30 pieces of silver. The chalice reeks of malice but holds the brew that is true - that is, if you're a vampire in need of resurrecting. And, since those ex-KGB agents have unearthed the coffin of Vlad Dracul, you can see where this is going. What I like best about TNT's Librarian series is that it's not at all pretentious. It wallows in its unabashed cheesiness and farce, even as it hunkers down with a pretty good adventure story. THE LIBRARIAN: CURSE OF THE JUDAS CHALICE is the third in the series, and it doesn't disappoint its fans. Hokey fun, mythical artifacts, indecipherable manuscripts, supernatural villains, and a likable, nebbish, talky hero (even the bad guys complain of his always talking in paragraphs). By now, Noah Wyle's got his part down cold. The neat thing about his character is that he can do something heroic but, then, subsequently have the rug pulled out from under him. And, when this happens, he's so damn good-natured about it. Flynn has had a hard time keeping his lady loves. First Nicole (Sonya Walger), then Emily Davenport (Gabrielle Anwar). This time out, Wyle's romantic interest is exotic Stana Katic, who plays bluesy singer Simone Renoir with femme fatale nuances. Maybe she's a keeper. Or not. Meanwhile, Jane Curtin and Bob Newhart (at his stammering best) are again solidly on board as the museum directors. I never thought I'd ever say this, but I had a better time with THE LIBRARIAN: CURSE OF THE JUDAS CHALICE than with that last Indiana Jones flick. This movie, like its predecessors (The Librarian - Quest for the Spear &The Librarian - Return to King Solomon's Mines) are tongue-in-cheek throwbacks to those high adventure pictures churned out back in the 1930s, '40s and '50s. I don't think I'm reaching that much when I say that even the score here is rousing enough that it actually reminded me of those Errol Flynn swashbucklers. But, of course, Flynn Carsen is no Errol Flynn. Errol doesn't know the Dewey Decimal System.

A few years ago when we still had Cable TV, I caught a few episodes of the TV Series "The Librarians" and recently bought the first 2 seasons to watch when I stumbled across the 3 movies. I opted to purchase the movies and have now watched the last of the 3 movies with the family and we all enjoyed it. I am glad that I will watch the movies first because it adds a lot of backstory to the Library and the characters. It's sort of like Raiders of the Lost Ark and Romancing the stone but I think it is better.

Jane Curtain & Bob Newhart reprise their roles and Flynn ends up in New Orleans searching for the Judas Chalice, and falls in love with a french singer who turns out to be a vampire (Stana Katic of Castle fame). I liked the movie a lot and am now looking forward to the rest of the series (Seasons 1, 2 and 3). We also learn more about the library and how it came to be.

I watched this movie for Kate Beckett's actress playing a (spoiler!) vampire with a heavy french accent, and I was not disappointed in that regard. It was hilarious and she was adorable. This movie, however, is heavy-handed and rife with racial stereotypes. The main character also gets dumped by a long term girlfriend, meets a new girl like a week later maximum, and over the course of three days falls so deeply in love that he offers to spend eternity with her. Uh-huh. Sure. Also, like, they wrote her out so awkwardly at the end? Are we really not done with vampire sun suicides? She couldn't just run off and join a travelling choir quartet or something? Nope, she was a loose end, can't have those hanging around. Ugh. Also, the special effects are rather hokey and dated, but I suppose that can't be helped. Still, a moderately enjoyable ride. And the Librarian series is beloved for its cheesiness, after all.

After the second Librarian movie went some strange places, I fully prepared myself for more craziness in The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice.  Sadly, this third made for TV movie went even further afield.

The movie opens with Flynn Carsen (Noah Wyle) on another life and death quest to save the world.  This time, hes in London at an auction bidding on an antique vase.  What he really wants is inside it, however, The Philosophers Stone.  While he succeeds at this mission, it costs him his current girlfriend.  Fed up, he goes on a rant when he gets home, and Judson and Charlene (Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin) suggest he take some of his unused vacation time.

However, after a couple of days, he finds himself growing bored.  After being encouraged to follow his dreams, he dreams of a beautiful woman in New Orleans.  Inspired to go visit the city, he actually finds her singing in a lounge in the city and learns her name is Simone (Stana Katic).  However, when people start chasing them, he hears a story of the Judas chalice and its connection to Judas Iscariot who some believe to be the first vampire.  Is any of it true?  Can he find it if it is?

Yes, you read that right.  This one involves yet another weird history for a Biblical character.  Somehow, this one just went too far for me.  If they had kept it about Vampires and not brought any connection into the Bible into it, I probably would have gone along with it.  However, this strange connection just made me uneasy and I couldn't quite enjoy it as a result.

Which is a shame because it is filled with the same fun as the first two films.  There are laughs and quips and action as Flynn once again must battle the forces of evil to save the world.  The plot has some great twists to it and really does have good entertainment to it, if you can get past the part of the premise I couldn't accept.

The effects are better than the previous film, although they still aren't completely up to big screen standards.  Then again, this is a made for TV budget, so that can be understood and forgiven.

The acting is pretty good as well.  I had a bit of trouble with Stana Katics heavy accent early on, but as the movie went along I was able to understand her better.  While the rest of the cast was great, I especially enjoyed seeing her in this since the next year, she went on to star as Kate Beckett in Castle, as show I still absolutely love.

So if you don't have the hang up I do with the premise, you will enjoy The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice.  There is some entertainment here; I just couldn't completely get past the premise.

The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice is the last of the Librarian (movie) trilogy.  (After that came the television series.)  In Judas Chalice, Flynn has been dumped by his most recent girlfriend.  Let's hear it: aaahhhh.  He takes a long needed vacation and ends up in The Big Easy where he meets Canadian hottie, Stana Katic as a vampire cum jazz singer, Simone.

The Judas Chalice, it is said, has the ability to revive Count Vlad and create serious bad ju-ju and mojo for the rest of the world.  Of course, Flynn won't have that.  His girl du jour, Simone, exposes herself to Flynn as a vampire created by Vlad.  She had been the keeper of a piece of the puzzle which would lead to the cup.  Guess what?  There's pirates, too!  Yes, good ole Jean Lafitte has the chalice in his treasure chest onboard his ship in Morgan's Bay.

Directed by Jonathan Frakes, these are campy movies with fun action, great zingers of one liners and pretty decent acting.  It's suitable for the entire family and should make a family movie night well worthwhile.

The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice (2008-tvm). Unrated. Running Time: One hour, 30 mins. Directed by Jonathan Frakes. Written by Marco Schnabel, David N. Titcher. Third tv-movie and was the last until 2014 and returned with a tv series. Returning: Noah Wyle, Bob Newhart, Jane Curtin. Flynn (Noah Wyle) is at the London Glen Auction dressed like James Bond. Charlene (Jane Curtin) whom is watching the bids on internet tells Flynn by cell phone to be careful with his bidding and what ever he does, don't let Ivan (Jason Douglas) walk away with the green Dynasty vase. Just then, Kate (Beth Burvant) calls Flynn. She has been stood up by Flynn and is an emotional wreck. He is late. While he is talking to Kate, the bid for the vase increases ever so high. Finally Flynn has the last bid of f1,000,000. Sold to Flynn. Charlene faints to the floor. Upon paying the bid, Flynn breaks the vase and finds the Philosopher's Stone inside. Ivan wants the stone and attempts to kill Flynn for it. How will Flynn get out of this? Well, back at the Metropolitan Public Library, Flynn gets a talking to from Charlene. The amount is way to high to pay, but then is shown another another secret large part of the library. it contains Noah's Ark and the Fountain of Youth. Flynn has a breakdown over the loss of his new girlfriend and losing other girlfriends because of this job. So Judson (Bob Newhart) and Charlene recommend vacation time. After getting drunk at a wine-tasting event, Charlene visits Flynn and gives him some traveling brochures. Flynn decides to take a trip to New Orleans. He meets Simone Renoir (Stana Katic), a singer at a club. This leads to an adventure of the Judas Chalice. Also in the cast: Bruce Davison, Dikran Tulaine, Joe Knezevich, Armando Leduc, Antonio Echeverria, Joe Ross, Jonathan Frakes. Filmed in Baton Rouge, Harahan, New Orleans, Louisiana. Hmm. I wonder where they got the idea for the Philosopher's Stone? Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone [Blu-ray] (2001). Language in English. Subtitles in Spanish. Special Features: Deleted Scenes. Visual Effects Deconstruction Sequences. A Look Behind the Monastery Scene. The Librarian - Quest for the Spear (2004-tvm). The Librarian - Return to King Solomon's Mines (2006-tvm). The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice (2008-tvm). The Librarians and the Crown of King Arthur (2014-tvm). The Librarians tv series (TNT, 2014-18).

I do recommend that you purchase at least the librarian the spear of destiny because this movie is based as a continuation of that one. The 3 movies are the spear of destiny, King Solomon's mines, curse of the Judas chalice in that order. And yes I recommend this movie, I truly recommend that you watch the other 2, 1st. That way you will have the continuity feel the only complaint that I have is that they never made any more.

Her dress in this movie was so tight you could see her reach down and pull it up just to be able to run in the action scenes.  I couldn't help but wonder how many takes it took in those scenes to get one where her dress actually stayed up and covered her that they could show.

I viewed this only to see Stana in an early venture that I was able to watch.  She definitely can sing which is another amazing GOD given talent she has been blessed with.  The character role allowed her to show some skills especially in the tender close up scenes.  I especially enjoyed her final scene, that is the Stana we all became enamored with in Castle.

Stana is a beautiful young lady, I like her acting very much, her talent is abundant and is a real throw back to the actresses of the 40's and early 50's who projected the emotions and feelings with a pose of posture a facial expression or a line said in a particular manner.  She can do the same (like she did in the first season of Castle), but today's Hollywood wants the female leads to swear like porn stars, speak with regular vulgarity, and expose body parts to the world.  No young lady should be made to do that just to work.  Stana is way to talented to have to do that, but it doesn't seem to matter to those in charge that her younger fans especially the young girls who idolize her watch and listen to what she says, what she does, and what she wears.  They don't care about them.

I pray that Stana or someone close to her will realize very soon how talented she really is and stop all this other nonsense and provide scripts and vehicles for her to really stretch and use the talent she has been blessed with.  Stana is so much better than what she has had to work in thus far in her film career.

I look forward to the time when I can view a movie with Stana in the female lead and enjoy the film and her character where I won't feel like I need a shower after sitting through it because of all the filth the movie industry throws at the viewing public today.

Vacation obtained after the temper tantrum many of us might wish we could throw at work the poor man finds there is actually no way he can escape either work or love, even while on vacation.

One could say that workwise his cup runneth over while the his love life returned with something of a bite, working its way towards poingnancy.

The writers did a good job with this, there's everything from voodoo to vampires woven into the storyline, but well woven. The special effects are above average for this type of film, the acting varies from deadpan to hilarious but is consistently of better than average quality - and New Orleans is always an excellent backdrop.

If you enjoyed Indiana Jones, you'll love The Librarian, too. He's witty, nerdy, at times accident prone, and he's Noah Wyle. With Bob Newhart and Jane Curtain rounding out the cast, the fun multiplies; and Stana Katic was great as Flynn Carsen's vampire love interest! The other two "Librarian" movies: "Quest for the Spear" and "Return to King Solomon's Mines" are great, but personally, I think "Curse of the Judas Chalice" is the best of the three! It has everything you could possibly want on a boring TV night: Action! Romance! Vampires! Humor! Cheese! All in all, it's wonderfully fun, light entertainment not to be taken seriously, and minus all the blood and gore that's already out there in almost everything else.

A friend of mine recommended this TV movie as the best of the series of 3 about "The Librarian," a fantasy adventure that makes me almost wish such magical wonders did really lurk behind the card catalog files and closed doors at the New York Public Library!  Being a big fan of "Castle" star Stana Katic also made this film a must-see for me, and her remarkably different character in this (and her surprising good singing voice in a sultry and haunting ballad) add even more to my appreciation.  Some people compare this to the Indiana Jones movies or the H. Rider Haggard movies, but this is really different enough in its own quirky way to stand alone on its own merits.  With good comedic touches by veterans Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin that add to the fun but never overwhelm, spoofs without being campy and is scary enough to make you worry about the main characters.  I would love to see more like this one!

The third entry in the Librarian franchise in many ways lives up to the standards set by the first two. There is an interesting and exciting story with great action, great characterization, and wonderful touches of humor. The romantic element is also present. Stana Katic absolutely burns out the pixels on the widescreen. She was perfectly cast. Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin are great supporting characters.

But in a number of respects this was a disappointment. First, the introduction of fantasy creatures (vampires) takes the series in an undesirable direction. I understand that vampires have been all the rage for the last few years but I think the move to horror elements is a mistake. I had similar misgivings about aliens being introduced into the Indiana Jones series - it just doesn't feel right. I think the ghosts seen in Return to King Solomon's Mines is about as far in the direction of fantasy creatures as this series should go.

Second, this film doesn't involve the same amount of globetrotting as the first two. All the action is in New Orleans. There is an opening scene in London but it probably wasn't filmed there. Each succeeding film in this series seems to do less and less location shooting. Maybe the budgets are too tight?

Additionally, the extras were fairly lame. The deleted scenes are more properly described as deleted lines.

But maybe that's just me. Despite the above, I enjoyed the film and look forward to future entries in the series. Recommended for fans of fantasy adventure.

You wouldn't think Noah Wylie could carry a comedy-adventure series, but you'd be wrong, because he has. Not only that, the series manages to be fun and exciting, without gratuitous violence, sex, or swearing. The casting is excellent, with Bob Newhart and Jane Curtain in wonderfully understated roles, and the plots are interesting. Yes, the movies are low budget, but so what? Exercise your imagination! Remember Buckaroo Banzai? Now there was a low budget adventure film! As far as the third Librarian episode is concerned, the story may not be quite as strong as the first, but the characterization of the main characters is gradually deepening, and I think over time many more people will realize how strong this series is becoming. The third film is obviously setting up a fourth, and my intuition says that may be the last, but I hope not -- keep them coming! The bottom line here is that all three Librarian movies are wonderful escapist family entertainment. That's to be treasured these days.

The plot has lots of holes and tries to do too much without sufficiently building suspense. The other characters seem even shallower than the Librarian.(Makes me really appreciate the old B-movies. )  The story takes some childish turns with the writers wanting us to believe that a magic sword (Excalibur) is the Librarian's "best friend".( Yuh). With today's vampire-mania, this third installation in the Librarian saga is perfectly positioned for success.  Noah Wyle (as Flynn Carson) and company (Bob Newhart as Judson and Jane Curtin as Charlene) are on the track, this time, of, not the Holy Grail, but its opposite number, the Judas Chalice, which, as Flynn learns, was instrumental in the creation of the very first vampire, its original owner Judas Iscariot--and has the power to create more of them with no nonsense about biting necks.  But Flynn is approaching burnout after battling evil in some 35 forms and losing several girlfriends to his hectic and unpredictable lifestyle.  When he finally resigns himself to the job, he finds that he isn't the only one in search of the Chalice: a former KGB officer (Dikran Tulaine), assisted by a handicapped college professor (Bruce Davison) who turns out to be a lot more than he seems, wants it to help him restore Russia to her former glory by assembling an undead and unkillable army of vamps.  Deciphering a string of clues in post-Katrina New Orleans and teaming up with a seductive Creole chanteuse (Stana Katic) who also isn't telling everything she knows, Flynn finds himself once again up to his ears in danger and learning some things about himself and the Library (particularly Judson, who may well be just as immortal as any bloodsucker not alive) that he never suspected before.  Jonathan Frakes of "Star Trek: The Next Generation" directs with a fine hand for pacing and the effects, as always, are top-notch.  Those who, like myself, enjoyed the two previous chapters in this franchise must definitely not miss this one.

This movie is actually the third installment in a series, and Flynn, the main character, is a librarian who goes on missions collecting rare and historic relics for the Metropolitan Library of New York. The library has a secret amazing basement filled with treasures from all over the world, and getting a glimpse of its wonders really adds to the fun of the show.

Flynn's character works well because he knows so much and adds pieces to the story through his random factual interludes and references. The Librarian's vast knowledge and love of information really brings the whole story together. He kind of teaches you, and the action and suspense are almost like extras. I doubt that all of the things he says are true, but they sure captured my attention and made me want to know more.

I liked the idea of the Judas Chalice having a vampiric history. Definitely a good twist in the plot. I am not usually into the vampire thing, but it was fun and suspenseful and not the boring, same-old stuff we're used to when it comes to those creatures of the night. I also liked the little love story between Flynn and Simone. It had its own little twist as well.

Bob Newhart is loveable as kooky Judson, and Jane Curtin is also good in her nerdy role. Noah Wyle really surprised me, though. He's funny and nerdy-hot and an action hero all at once. It's Indiana Jones-esque. I think Wyle makes the perfect Librarian. I definitely want to see the rest of the series now. I hope they make many more. Definitely recommended.

This movie is either a low budget production meant to make money or a made-for-TV movie's DVD release meant to make more money. In either case we have sophomoric acting & a disjointed script with attempts at light humor. Or was it satire? No matter, hard to tell because it failed at both. Green screen generated backdrops were obviously low budget as shown by a total of two or three CG effects - blurry fast people and dying sparkly, already dead people. Both effects seen in countless other fantasy movies the past 8 years. The movie is also one improbable event after another including a librarian whose brain contains a data base the size of the Library of Congress. On the positive side: a pretty good ending where for the first time there was some emotive acting.
